
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `kbd_mode` baraye tagheer daadan vaz’iat (mode) keyboard dar console Linux estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma ejazeh midehad keyboard ra be vaz’iat-haye mokhtalef, mesle ASCII ya UTF-8, tagheer dahid.  

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `kbd_mode -a`  --> ⌨️ Gozashtan keyboard be vaz'iat ASCII. Dar in vaz'iat, karakter-haye ASCII tanha ghabele estefade hastand.
    🔹 `kbd_mode -u`  --> 🌐 Gozashtan keyboard be vaz'iat UTF-8. Dar in vaz'iat, shoma mitavanid hameye karakter-haye UTF-8 ra type konid.
    🔹 `kbd_mode -s`  --> ℹ️ Namayesh vaz'iat فعلی keyboard.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ kbd_mode -a

    🔹 Tagheer keyboard be vaz’iat ASCII.

    $ kbd_mode -u

    🔹 Tagheer keyboard be vaz’iat UTF-8.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ kbd_mode -s

    🔹 Namayesh midehad ke aya keyboard dar vaz’iat ASCII ast ya UTF-8. In baraye check kardane vaz'iat فعلی keyboard mofeed ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `kbd_mode` command is used to change the keyboard mode in the Linux console. It allows you to switch the keyboard to different modes, such as ASCII or UTF-8.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `kbd_mode -a`  --> ⌨️ Set the keyboard to ASCII mode. In this mode, only ASCII characters can be used.
    🔹 `kbd_mode -u`  --> 🌐 Set the keyboard to UTF-8 mode. In this mode, you can type all UTF-8 characters.
    🔹 `kbd_mode -s`  --> ℹ️ Display the current keyboard mode.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ kbd_mode -a

    🔹 Change the keyboard to ASCII mode.

    $ kbd_mode -u

    🔹 Change the keyboard to UTF-8 mode.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ kbd_mode -s

    🔹 Displays whether the keyboard is in ASCII or UTF-8 mode. This is useful for checking the current keyboard status.

